sec-set.prototype.entries.title: Set.prototype.entries()

sec-set.prototype.foreach.name: forEach
sec-set.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once for each value in the Set object, in insertion order.
sec-set.prototype.foreach.title: Set.prototype.forEach()

sec-set.prototype.has.name: has
sec-set.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified value exists in a Set object or not.
sec-set.prototype.has.title: Set.prototype.has()

sec-get-set.prototype.size.name: size
sec-get-set.prototype.size.summary: The size accessor property of Set instances returns the number of (unique) elements in this set.

firefox.notes: From Firefox 13 to Firefox 18, the size property was implemented as a Set.prototype.size() method, this has been changed to a property in later versions conform to the ECMAScript 2015 specification.

sec-get-set.prototype.size.title: Set.prototype.size

sec-set.prototype.values.name: values
sec-set.prototype.values.summary: The values() method returns a new set iterator object that contains the values for each element in the Set object in insertion order.
sec-set.prototype.values.title: Set.prototype.values()

sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.name: @@iterator
sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.summary: The [@@iterator]() method of Set instances implements the iterable protocol and allows sets to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. It returns an set iterator object that yields the values of the set in insertion order.

firefox.notes: A placeholder property named @@iterator is used.
A placeholder property named iterator is used.

sec-set.prototype-@@iterator.title: Set.prototype[@@iterator]()

sec-get-set-@@species.name: @@species
sec-get-set-@@species.summary: The Set[@@species] static accessor property is an unused accessor property specifying how to copy Set objects.
sec-get-set-@@species.title: Set[@@species]

sec-set-objects.name: Set
sec-set-objects.summary: The Set object lets you store unique values of any type, whether primitive values or object references.
sec-set-objects.title: Set

sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.name: SharedArrayBuffer
sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer() constructor creates SharedArrayBuffer objects.
sec-sharedarraybuffer-constructor.title: SharedArrayBuffer() constructor

sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.name: byteLength
sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.summary: The byteLength accessor property of SharedArrayBuffer instances returns the length (in bytes) of this SharedArrayBuffer.
sec-get-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.byte.title: SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.byteLength

sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method of SharedArrayBuffer instances returns a new SharedArrayBuffer whose contents are a copy of this SharedArrayBuffer's bytes from begin, inclusive, up to end, exclusive. If either begin or end is negative, it refers to an index from the end of the array, as opposed to from the beginning. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.slice().
sec-sharedarraybuffer.prototype.slice.title: SharedArrayBuffer.prototype.slice()

sec-sharedarraybuffer-@@species.name: @@species
sec-sharedarraybuffer-@@species.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer[@@species] static accessor property returns the constructor used to construct return values from SharedArrayBuffer methods.
sec-sharedarraybuffer-@@species.title: SharedArrayBuffer[@@species]

sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.name: SharedArrayBuffer
sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.summary: The SharedArrayBuffer object is used to represent a generic raw binary data buffer, similar to the ArrayBuffer object, but in a way that they can be used to create views on shared memory. A SharedArrayBuffer is not a Transferable Object, unlike an ArrayBuffer which is transferable.
sec-sharedarraybuffer-objects.title: SharedArrayBuffer

sec-string-constructor.name: String
sec-string-constructor.summary: The String() constructor creates String objects. When called as a function, it returns primitive values of type String.
sec-string-constructor.title: String() constructor

sec-string.prototype.at.name: at
sec-string.prototype.at.summary: The at() method takes an integer value and returns a new String consisting of the single UTF-16 code unit located at the specified offset. This method allows for positive and negative integers. Negative integers count back from the last string character.
sec-string.prototype.at.title: String.prototype.at()

sec-string.prototype.charat.name: charAt
sec-string.prototype.charat.summary: The charAt() method of String values returns a new string consisting of the single UTF-16 code unit at the given index.
sec-string.prototype.charat.title: String.prototype.charAt()

sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.name: charCodeAt
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.summary: The charCodeAt() method of String values returns an integer between 0 and 65535 representing the UTF-16 code unit at the given index.
sec-string.prototype.charcodeat.title: String.prototype.charCodeAt()

sec-string.prototype.codepointat.name: codePointAt
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.summary: The codePointAt() method of String values returns a non-negative integer that is the Unicode code point value of the character starting at the given index. Note that the index is still based on UTF-16 code units, not Unicode code points.
sec-string.prototype.codepointat.title: String.prototype.codePointAt()

sec-string.prototype.concat.name: concat
sec-string.prototype.concat.summary: The concat() method concatenates the string arguments to the calling string and returns a new string.
sec-string.prototype.concat.title: String.prototype.concat()

sec-string.prototype.endswith.name: endsWith
sec-string.prototype.endswith.summary: The endsWith() method determines whether a string ends with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.endswith.title: String.prototype.endsWith()

sec-string.fromcharcode.name: fromCharCode
sec-string.fromcharcode.summary: The String.fromCharCode() static method returns a string created from the specified sequence of UTF-16 code units.
sec-string.fromcharcode.title: String.fromCharCode()

sec-string.fromcodepoint.name: fromCodePoint
sec-string.fromcodepoint.summary: The String.fromCodePoint() static method returns a string created from the specified sequence of code points.
sec-string.fromcodepoint.title: String.fromCodePoint()

sec-string.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-string.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method performs a case-sensitive search to determine whether one string may be found within another string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.includes.title: String.prototype.includes()

sec-string.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-string.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method of String values searches this string and returns the index of the first occurrence of the specified substring. It takes an optional starting position and returns the first occurrence of the specified substring at an index greater than or equal to the specified number.
sec-string.prototype.indexof.title: String.prototype.indexOf()

sec-string.prototype.iswellformed.name: isWellFormed
sec-string.prototype.iswellformed.summary: The isWellFormed() method of String values returns a boolean indicating whether this string contains any lone surrogates.
sec-string.prototype.iswellformed.title: String.prototype.isWellFormed()

sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.summary: The lastIndexOf() method of String values searches this string and returns the index of the last occurrence of the specified substring. It takes an optional starting position and returns the last occurrence of the specified substring at an index less than or equal to the specified number.
sec-string.prototype.lastindexof.title: String.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.name: length
sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.summary: The length data property of a String value contains the length of the string in UTF-16 code units.
sec-properties-of-string-instances-lengt.title: String: length

sec-string.prototype.localecompare.name: localeCompare
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.summary: The localeCompare() method returns a number indicating whether a reference string comes before, or after, or is the same as the given string in sort order. In implementations with Intl.Collator API support, this method simply calls Intl.Collator.
sec-string.prototype.localecompare.title: String.prototype.localeCompare()

sec-string.prototype.match.name: match
sec-string.prototype.match.summary: The match() method retrieves the result of matching a string against a regular expression.
sec-string.prototype.match.title: String.prototype.match()

sec-string.prototype.matchall.name: matchAll
sec-string.prototype.matchall.summary: The matchAll() method returns an iterator of all results matching a string against a regular expression, including capturing groups.
sec-string.prototype.matchall.title: String.prototype.matchAll()

sec-string.prototype.normalize.name: normalize
sec-string.prototype.normalize.summary: The normalize() method returns the Unicode Normalization Form of the string.
sec-string.prototype.normalize.title: String.prototype.normalize()

sec-string.prototype.padend.name: padEnd
sec-string.prototype.padend.summary: The padEnd() method pads the current string with a given string (repeated, if needed) so that the resulting string reaches a given length. The padding is applied from the end of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padend.title: String.prototype.padEnd()

sec-string.prototype.padstart.name: padStart
sec-string.prototype.padstart.summary: The padStart() method pads the current string with another string (multiple times, if needed) until the resulting string reaches the given length. The padding is applied from the start of the current string.
sec-string.prototype.padstart.title: String.prototype.padStart()

sec-string.raw.name: raw
sec-string.raw.summary: The String.raw() static method is a tag function of template literals. This is similar to the r prefix in Python, or the @ prefix in C# for string literals. It's used to get the raw string form of template literals  that is, substitutions (e.g. ${foo}) are processed, but escape sequences (e.g. \n) are not.
sec-string.raw.title: String.raw()

sec-string.prototype.repeat.name: repeat
sec-string.prototype.repeat.summary: The repeat() method constructs and returns a new string which contains the specified number of copies of the string on which it was called, concatenated together.
sec-string.prototype.repeat.title: String.prototype.repeat()

sec-string.prototype.replace.name: replace
sec-string.prototype.replace.summary: The replace() method returns a new string with one, some, or all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement. The pattern can be a string or a RegExp, and the replacement can be a string or a function called for each match. If pattern is a string, only the first occurrence will be replaced. The original string is left unchanged.

ie.notes: A replacement function as second argument is not supported.

sec-string.prototype.replace.title: String.prototype.replace()

sec-string.prototype.replaceall.name: replaceAll
sec-string.prototype.replaceall.summary: The replaceAll() method returns a new string with all matches of a pattern replaced by a replacement. The pattern can be a string or a RegExp, and the replacement can be a string or a function to be called for each match. The original string is left unchanged.
sec-string.prototype.replaceall.title: String.prototype.replaceAll()

sec-string.prototype.search.name: search
sec-string.prototype.search.summary: The search() method executes a search for a match between a regular expression and this String object.
sec-string.prototype.search.title: String.prototype.search()

sec-string.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-string.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method extracts a section of a string and returns it as a new string, without modifying the original string.
sec-string.prototype.slice.title: String.prototype.slice()

sec-string.prototype.split.name: split
sec-string.prototype.split.summary: The split() method takes a pattern and divides a String into an ordered list of substrings by searching for the pattern, puts these substrings into an array, and returns the array.
sec-string.prototype.split.title: String.prototype.split()

sec-string.prototype.startswith.name: startsWith
sec-string.prototype.startswith.summary: The startsWith() method determines whether a string begins with the characters of a specified string, returning true or false as appropriate.
sec-string.prototype.startswith.title: String.prototype.startsWith()

sec-string.prototype.substring.name: substring
sec-string.prototype.substring.summary: The substring() method returns the part of the string from the start index up to and excluding the end index, or to the end of the string if no end index is supplied.
sec-string.prototype.substring.title: String.prototype.substring()

sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.name: toLocaleLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.summary: The toLocaleLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocalelowercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.name: toLocaleUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.summary: The toLocaleUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to upper case, according to any locale-specific case mappings.
sec-string.prototype.tolocaleuppercase.title: String.prototype.toLocaleUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.name: toLowerCase
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.summary: The toLowerCase() method returns the calling string value converted to lower case.
sec-string.prototype.tolowercase.title: String.prototype.toLowerCase()

sec-string.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-string.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified string value.
sec-string.prototype.tostring.title: String.prototype.toString()

sec-string.prototype.touppercase.name: toUpperCase
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.summary: The toUpperCase() method returns the calling string value converted to uppercase (the value will be converted to a string if it isn't one).
sec-string.prototype.touppercase.title: String.prototype.toUpperCase()

sec-string.prototype.towellformed.name: toWellFormed
sec-string.prototype.towellformed.summary: The toWellFormed() method of String values returns a string where all lone surrogates of this string are replaced with the Unicode replacement character U+FFFD.
sec-string.prototype.towellformed.title: String.prototype.toWellFormed()

sec-string.prototype.trim.name: trim
sec-string.prototype.trim.summary: The trim() method removes whitespace from both ends of a string and returns a new string, without modifying the original string.
sec-string.prototype.trim.title: String.prototype.trim()

sec-string.prototype.trimend.name: trimEnd
sec-string.prototype.trimend.summary: The trimEnd() method removes whitespace from the end of a string and returns a new string, without modifying the original string. trimRight() is an alias of this method.
sec-string.prototype.trimend.title: String.prototype.trimEnd()

sec-string.prototype.trimstart.name: trimStart
sec-string.prototype.trimstart.summary: The trimStart() method removes whitespace from the beginning of a string and returns a new string, without modifying the original string. trimLeft() is an alias of this method.
sec-string.prototype.trimstart.title: String.prototype.trimStart()

sec-string.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-string.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a String object.
sec-string.prototype.valueof.title: String.prototype.valueOf()

sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.name: @@iterator
sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.summary: The [@@iterator]() method of String values implements the iterable protocol and allows strings to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. It returns a string iterator object that yields the Unicode code points of the string value as individual strings.

firefox.notes: A placeholder property named @@iterator is used.
A placeholder property named iterator is used.

sec-string.prototype-@@iterator.title: String.prototype[@@iterator]()

sec-string-objects.name: String
sec-string-objects.summary: The String object is used to represent and manipulate a sequence of characters.
sec-string-objects.title: String

sec-symbol-constructor.name: Symbol
sec-symbol-constructor.summary: The Symbol() function returns primitive values of type Symbol.
sec-symbol-constructor.title: Symbol() constructor

sec-symbol.asynciterator.name: asyncIterator
sec-symbol.asynciterator.summary: The Symbol.asyncIterator static data property represents the well-known symbol @@asyncIterator. The async iterable protocol looks up this symbol for the method that returns the async iterator for an object. In order for an object to be async iterable, it must have an @@asyncIterator key.
sec-symbol.asynciterator.title: Symbol.asyncIterator

sec-symbol.prototype.description.name: description
sec-symbol.prototype.description.summary: The description accessor property of Symbol values returns a string containing the description of this symbol, or undefined if the symbol has no description.

safari.notes: No support for an undefined description.

sec-symbol.prototype.description.title: Symbol.prototype.description

sec-symbol.for.name: for
sec-symbol.for.summary: The Symbol.for() static method searches for existing symbols in a runtime-wide symbol registry with the given key and returns it if found. Otherwise a new symbol gets created in the global symbol registry with this key.
sec-symbol.for.title: Symbol.for()

sec-symbol.hasinstance.name: hasInstance
sec-symbol.hasinstance.summary: The Symbol.hasInstance static data property represents the well-known symbol @@hasInstance. The instanceof operator looks up this symbol on its right-hand operand for the method used to determine if the constructor object recognizes an object as its instance.
sec-symbol.hasinstance.title: Symbol.hasInstance

sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.name: isConcatSpreadable
sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.summary: The Symbol.isConcatSpreadable static data property represents the well-known symbol @@isConcatSpreadable. The Array.prototype.concat() method looks up this symbol on each object being concatenated to determine if it should be treated as an array-like object and flattened to its array elements.
sec-symbol.isconcatspreadable.title: Symbol.isConcatSpreadable

sec-symbol.iterator.name: iterator
sec-symbol.iterator.summary: The Symbol.iterator static data property represents the well-known symbol @@iterator. The iterable protocol looks up this symbol for the method that returns the iterator for an object. In order for an object to be iterable, it must have an @@iterator key.
sec-symbol.iterator.title: Symbol.iterator

sec-symbol.keyfor.name: keyFor
sec-symbol.keyfor.summary: The Symbol.keyFor() static method retrieves a shared symbol key from the global symbol registry for the given symbol.
sec-symbol.keyfor.title: Symbol.keyFor()

sec-symbol.match.name: match
sec-symbol.match.summary: The Symbol.match static data property represents the well-known symbol @@match. The String.prototype.match() method looks up this symbol on its first argument for the method used to match an input string against the current object. This symbol is also used to determine if an object should be treated as a regex.
sec-symbol.match.title: Symbol.match

sec-symbol.matchall.name: matchAll
sec-symbol.matchall.summary: The Symbol.matchAll static data property represents the well-known symbol @@matchAll. The String.prototype.matchAll() method looks up this symbol on its first argument for the method that returns an iterator, that yields matches of the current object against a string.
sec-symbol.matchall.title: Symbol.matchAll

sec-symbol.replace.name: replace
sec-symbol.replace.summary: The Symbol.replace static data property represents the well-known symbol @@replace. The String.prototype.replace() method looks up this symbol on its first argument for the method that replaces substrings matched by the current object.
sec-symbol.replace.title: Symbol.replace

sec-symbol.search.name: search
sec-symbol.search.summary: The Symbol.search static data property represents the well-known symbol @@search. The String.prototype.search() method looks up this symbol on its first argument for the method that returns the index within a string that matches the current object.
sec-symbol.search.title: Symbol.search

sec-symbol.species.name: species
sec-symbol.species.summary: The Symbol.species static data property represents the well-known symbol @@species. Methods that create copies of an object may look up this symbol on the object for the constructor function to use when creating the copy.
sec-symbol.species.title: Symbol.species

sec-symbol.split.name: split
sec-symbol.split.summary: The Symbol.split static data property represents the well-known symbol @@split. The String.prototype.split() method looks up this symbol on its first argument for the method that splits a string at the indices that match the current object.
sec-symbol.split.title: Symbol.split

sec-symbol.toprimitive.name: toPrimitive
sec-symbol.toprimitive.summary: The Symbol.toPrimitive static data property represents the well-known symbol @@toPrimitive. All type coercion algorithms look up this symbol on objects for the method that accepts a preferred type and returns a primitive representation of the object, before falling back to using the object's valueOf() and toString() methods.
sec-symbol.toprimitive.title: Symbol.toPrimitive

sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified symbol value.
sec-symbol.prototype.tostring.title: Symbol.prototype.toString()

sec-symbol.tostringtag.name: toStringTag
sec-symbol.tostringtag.summary: The Symbol.toStringTag static data property represents the well-known symbol @@toStringTag. Object.prototype.toString() looks up this symbol on the this value for the property containing a string that represents the type of the object.
sec-symbol.tostringtag.title: Symbol.toStringTag

sec-symbol.unscopables.name: unscopables
sec-symbol.unscopables.summary: The Symbol.unscopables static data property represents the well-known symbol @@unscopables. The with statement looks up this symbol on the scope object for a property containing a collection of properties that should not become bindings within the with environment.
sec-symbol.unscopables.title: Symbol.unscopables

sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.name: valueOf
sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.summary: The valueOf() method returns the primitive value of a Symbol object.
sec-symbol.prototype.valueof.title: Symbol.prototype.valueOf()

sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.name: @@toPrimitive
sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.summary: The [@@toPrimitive]() method converts a Symbol object to a primitive value.
sec-symbol.prototype-@@toprimitive.title: Symbol.prototype[@@toPrimitive]()

sec-symbol-objects.name: Symbol
sec-symbol-objects.summary: Symbol is a built-in object whose constructor returns a symbol primitive  also called a Symbol value or just a Symbol  that's guaranteed to be unique. Symbols are often used to add unique property keys to an object that won't collide with keys any other code might add to the object, and which are hidden from any mechanisms other code will typically use to access the object. That enables a form of weak encapsulation, or a weak form of information hiding.
sec-symbol-objects.title: Symbol

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: SyntaxError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The SyntaxError object represents an error when trying to interpret syntactically invalid code. It is thrown when the JavaScript engine encounters tokens or token order that does not conform to the syntax of the language when parsing code.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: SyntaxError

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: TypeError
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.summary: The TypeError object represents an error when an operation could not be performed, typically (but not exclusively) when a value is not of the expected type.
sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.title: TypeError

sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.name: BYTES_PER_ELEMENT
sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.summary: The TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT static data property represents the size in bytes of each element in a typed array.
sec-typedarray.bytes_per_element.title: TypedArray.BYTES_PER_ELEMENT

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.name: at
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.summary: The at() method takes an integer value and returns the item at that index, allowing for positive and negative integers. Negative integers count back from the last item in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.at.title: TypedArray.prototype.at()

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.name: buffer
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.summary: The buffer accessor property of TypedArray instances returns the ArrayBuffer or SharedArrayBuffer referenced by this typed array at construction time.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.buffer.title: TypedArray.prototype.buffer

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.name: byteLength
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.summary: The byteLength accessor property of TypedArray instances returns the length (in bytes) of this typed array.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.bytelengt.title: TypedArray.prototype.byteLength

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.name: byteOffset
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.summary: The byteOffset accessor property of TypedArray instances returns the offset (in bytes) of this typed array from the start of its ArrayBuffer or SharedArrayBuffer.
sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.byteoffse.title: TypedArray.prototype.byteOffset

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.name: copyWithin
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.summary: The copyWithin() method copies the sequence of array elements within the array to the position starting at target. The copy is taken from the index positions of the second and third arguments start and end. The end argument is optional and defaults to the length of the array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.copyWithin. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.copywithin.title: TypedArray.prototype.copyWithin()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.name: entries
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.summary: The entries() method returns a new array iterator that contains the key/value pairs for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.entries.title: TypedArray.prototype.entries()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.name: every
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.summary: The every() method tests whether all elements in the typed array pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.every(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.every.title: TypedArray.prototype.every()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.name: fill
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.summary: The fill() method fills all the elements of a typed array from a start index to an end index with a static value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.fill(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.fill.title: TypedArray.prototype.fill()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.name: filter
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.summary: The filter() method creates a new typed array with all elements that pass the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.filter(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.filter.title: TypedArray.prototype.filter()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.name: find
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.summary: The find() method returns a value of an element in the typed array, if it satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise undefined is returned. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.find.title: TypedArray.prototype.find()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.name: findIndex
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.summary: The findIndex() method returns an index in the typed array, if an element in the typed array satisfies the provided testing function. Otherwise -1 is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findindex.title: TypedArray.prototype.findIndex()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.name: findLast
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.summary: The findLast() method iterates a typed array in reverse order and returns the value of the first element that satisfies the provided testing function. If no values satisfy the testing function, undefined is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlast.title: TypedArray.prototype.findLast()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.name: findLastIndex
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.summary: The findLastIndex() method iterates a typed array in reverse order and returns the index of the first element that satisfies the provided testing function. If no values satisfy the testing function, -1 is returned.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.findlastindex.title: TypedArray.prototype.findLastIndex()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.name: forEach
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.summary: The forEach() method executes a provided function once per array element. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.forEach(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.foreach.title: TypedArray.prototype.forEach()

sec-%typedarray%.from.name: from
sec-%typedarray%.from.summary: The TypedArray.from() static method creates a new typed array from an array-like or iterable object. This method is nearly the same as Array.from().
sec-%typedarray%.from.title: TypedArray.from()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.name: includes
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.summary: The includes() method determines whether a typed array includes a certain element, returning true or false as appropriate. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.includes(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.includes.title: TypedArray.prototype.includes()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.name: indexOf
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.summary: The indexOf() method returns the first index at which a given element can be found in the typed array, or -1 if it is not present. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.indexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 47, this method will no longer return -0. For example, new Uint8Array([0]).indexOf(0, -0) will now always return +0.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.indexof.title: TypedArray.prototype.indexOf()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.name: join
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.summary: The join() method joins all elements of an array into a string. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.join(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.join.title: TypedArray.prototype.join()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.name: keys
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.summary: The keys() method returns a new array iterator object that contains the keys for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.keys.title: TypedArray.prototype.keys()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.name: lastIndexOf

The typed array is searched backwards, starting at fromIndex. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.lastIndexOf(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 47, this method will no longer return -0. For example, new Uint8Array([0]).lastIndexOf(0, -0) will now always return +0.

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.lastindexof.title: TypedArray.prototype.lastIndexOf()

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.length.name: length

sec-get-%typedarray%.prototype.length.title: TypedArray.prototype.length

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.name: map
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.summary: The map() method creates a new typed array with the results of calling a provided function on every element in this typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.map(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.map.title: TypedArray.prototype.map()

sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.name: name
sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.summary: The name data property of a Function instance indicates the function's name as specified when it was created, or it may be either anonymous or '' (an empty string) for functions created anonymously.
sec-properties-of-the-typedarray-constru.title: Function: name

sec-%typedarray%.of.name: of
sec-%typedarray%.of.summary: The TypedArray.of() static method creates a new typed array from a variable number of arguments. This method is nearly the same as Array.of().
sec-%typedarray%.of.title: TypedArray.of()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.name: reduce
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.summary: The reduce() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from left-to-right) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduce(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduce.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduce()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.name: reduceRight
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.summary: The reduceRight() method applies a function against an accumulator and each value of the typed array (from right-to-left) has to reduce it to a single value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reduceRight(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reduceright.title: TypedArray.prototype.reduceRight()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.name: reverse
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.summary: The reverse() method reverses a typed array in place. The first typed array element becomes the last and the last becomes the first. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reverse(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.reverse.title: TypedArray.prototype.reverse()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.name: set
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.summary: The set() method stores multiple values in the typed array, reading input values from a specified array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.set.title: TypedArray.prototype.set()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.name: slice
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.summary: The slice() method returns a new typed array (with a new underlying buffer), that contains a copy of a portion of the original typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.slice(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.slice.title: TypedArray.prototype.slice()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.name: some
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.summary: The some() method tests whether some element in the typed array passes the test implemented by the provided function. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.some(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.some.title: TypedArray.prototype.some()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.name: sort
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.summary: The sort() method sorts the elements of a typed array numerically in place and returns the typed array. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.sort(), except that it sorts the values numerically instead of as strings by default. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.sort.title: TypedArray.prototype.sort()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.name: subarray
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.summary: The subarray() method returns a new TypedArray on the same ArrayBuffer store and with the same element types as for this TypedArray object. The begin offset is inclusive and the end offset is exclusive. TypedArray is one of the typed array types.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.subarray.title: TypedArray.prototype.subarray()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.name: toLocaleString
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.summary: The toLocaleString() method returns a string representing the elements of the typed array. The elements are converted to strings and are separated by a locale-specific string (such as a comma ","). This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toLocaleString() and, as the typed array elements are numbers, the same algorithm as Number.prototype.toLocaleString() applies for each element. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tolocalestrin.title: TypedArray.prototype.toLocaleString()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.toreversed.name: toReversed
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.toreversed.summary: The toReversed() method is the copying counterpart of the reverse() method. It returns a new array with the elements in reversed order. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.reverse(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.toreversed.title: TypedArray.prototype.toReversed()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tosorted.name: toSorted
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tosorted.summary: The toSorted() method is the copying version of the sort() method. It returns a new array with the elements sorted in ascending order. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toSorted(), except that it sorts the values numerically instead of as strings by default. TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tosorted.title: TypedArray.prototype.toSorted()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tostring.name: toString
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tostring.summary: The toString() method returns a string representing the specified array and its elements. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.toString(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.tostring.title: TypedArray.prototype.toString()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.values.name: values
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.values.summary: The values() method returns a new array iterator object that contains the values for each index in the array.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.values.title: TypedArray.prototype.values()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype.with.name: with
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.with.summary: The with() method is the copying version of using the bracket notation to change the value of a given index. It returns a new array with the element at the given index replaced with the given value. This method has the same algorithm as Array.prototype.with(). TypedArray is one of the typed array types here.
sec-%typedarray%.prototype.with.title: TypedArray.prototype.with()

sec-%typedarray%.prototype-@@iterator.name: @@iterator
sec-%typedarray%.prototype-@@iterator.summary: The [@@iterator]() method of TypedArray instances implements the iterable protocol and allows typed arrays to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. It returns an array iterator object that yields the value of each index in the typed array.

sec-get-%typedarray%-@@species.name: @@species

sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.name: delete

sec-weakmap.prototype.delete.title: WeakMap.prototype.delete()

sec-weakmap.prototype.get.name: get
sec-weakmap.prototype.get.summary: The get() method returns a specified element from a WeakMap object.

sec-weakmap.prototype.get.title: WeakMap.prototype.get()

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.name: has
sec-weakmap.prototype.has.summary: The has() method returns a boolean indicating whether an element with the specified key exists in the WeakMap object or not.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.has.title: WeakMap.prototype.has()

sec-weakmap.prototype.set.name: set
sec-weakmap.prototype.set.summary: The set() method adds a new element with a specified key and value to a WeakMap object.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 38, this method threw a TypeError when the key parameter was not an object. This has been fixed in version 38 and later to return false as per the ES2015 standard.

sec-weakmap.prototype.set.title: WeakMap.prototype.set()

sec-weakmap-objects.name: WeakMap
sec-weakmap-objects.summary: A WeakMap is a collection of key/value pairs whose keys must be objects or non-registered symbols, with values of any arbitrary JavaScript type, and which does not create strong references to its keys. That is, an object's presence as a key in a WeakMap does not prevent the object from being garbage collected. Once an object used as a key has been collected, its corresponding values in any WeakMap become candidates for garbage collection as well  as long as they aren't strongly referred to elsewhere. The only primitive type that can be used as a WeakMap key is symbol  more specifically, non-registered symbols  because non-registered symbols are guaranteed to be unique and cannot be re-created.
sec-weakmap-objects.title: WeakMap

sec-weak-ref-constructor.name: WeakRef
sec-weak-ref-constructor.summary: The WeakRef() constructor creates WeakRef objects.

sec-weak-ref.prototype.deref.name: deref

sec-weak-ref.prototype.deref.title: WeakRef.prototype.deref()

sec-weak-ref-objects.name: WeakRef
sec-weak-ref-objects.summary: A WeakRef object lets you hold a weak reference to another object, without preventing that object from getting garbage-collected.
sec-weak-ref-objects.title: WeakRef

sec-weakset-constructor.name: WeakSet

sec-weakset.prototype.add.name: add

sec-weakset-objects.name: WeakSet
sec-weakset-objects.summary: A WeakSet is a collection of garbage-collectable values, including objects and non-registered symbols. A value in the WeakSet may only occur once. It is unique in the WeakSet's collection.
sec-weakset-objects.title: WeakSet

sec-native-error-types-used-in-this-stan.name: CompileError

sec-decodeuricomponent-encodeduricompone.summary: The decodeURIComponent() function decodes a Uniform Resource Identifier (URI) component previously created by encodeURIComponent() or by a similar routine.

sec-encodeuri-uri.name: encodeURI
sec-encodeuri-uri.summary: The encodeURI() function encodes a URI by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two surrogate characters). sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.name: encodeURIComponent
sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.summary: The encodeURIComponent() function encodes a URI by replacing each instance of certain characters by one, two, three, or four escape sequences representing the UTF-8 encoding of the character (will only be four escape sequences for characters composed of two surrogate characters). Compared to encodeURI(), this function encodes more characters, including those that are part of the URI syntax.
sec-encodeuricomponent-uricomponent.title: encodeURIComponent()

sec-eval-x.name: eval
sec-eval-x.summary: The eval() function evaluates JavaScript code represented as a string and returns its completion value. The source is parsed as a script.
sec-eval-x.title: eval()

sec-globalthis.name: globalThis
sec-globalthis.summary: The globalThis global property contains the global this value, which is usually akin to the global object.

sec-isfinite-number.name: isFinite
sec-isfinite-number.summary: The isFinite() function determines whether the passed value is a finite number. If needed, the parameter is first converted to a number.
sec-isfinite-number.title: isFinite()

sec-isnan-number.name: isNaN
sec-isnan-number.summary: The isNaN() function determines whether a value is NaN when converted to a number. Because coercion inside the isNaN() function can be surprising, you may alternatively want to use Number.isNaN().
sec-isnan-number.title: isNaN()

sec-parsefloat-string.name: parseFloat
sec-parsefloat-string.summary: The parseFloat() function parses a string argument and returns a floating point number.
sec-parsefloat-string.title: parseFloat()

sec-parseint-string-radix.name: parseInt
sec-parseint-string-radix.summary: The parseInt() function parses a string argument and returns an integer of the specified radix (the base in mathematical numeral systems).
sec-parseint-string-radix.title: parseInt()

sec-undefined.summary: The undefined global property represents the primitive value undefined. It is one of JavaScript's primitive types.

sec-static-semantics-constructormethod.summary: The constructor method is a special method of a class for creating and initializing an object instance of that class.

sec-class-definitions.title: static

sec-class-definitions.name: classes
sec-class-definitions.summary: Classes are a template for creating objects. They encapsulate data with code to work on that data. Classes in JS are built on prototypes but also have some syntax and semantics that are unique to classes.

sec-arguments-exotic-objects.name: length
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.summary: The arguments.length data property contains the number of arguments passed to the function.
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.title: arguments.length

sec-arguments-exotic-objects.name: arguments
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.summary: arguments is an array-like object accessible inside functions that contains the values of the arguments passed to that function.
sec-arguments-exotic-objects.title: The arguments object

sec-createunmappedargumentsobject.summary: The [@@iterator]() method of arguments objects implements the iterable protocol and allows arguments objects to be consumed by most syntaxes expecting iterables, such as the spread syntax and for...of loops. sec-function-definitions.title: Rest parameters

sec-function-definitions.title: function declaration

sec-method-definitions.summary: The get syntax binds an object property to a function that will be called when that property is looked up. It can also be used in classes.
sec-method-definitions.title: get

sec-method-definitions.name: method_definitions
sec-method-definitions.summary: Method definition is a shorter syntax for defining a function property in an object initializer. It can also be used in classes.

sec-array-initializer.name: array_literals
sec-array-initializer.summary: This page describes JavaScript's lexical grammar. JavaScript source text is just a sequence of characters  in order for the interpreter to understand it, the string has to be parsed to a more structured representation. The initial step of parsing is called lexical analysis, in which the text gets scanned from left to right and is converted into a sequence of individual, atomic input elements. Some input elements are insignificant to the interpreter, and will be stripped after this step  they include white space and comments. The others, including identifiers, keywords, literals, and punctuators (mostly operators), will be used for further syntax analysis. Line terminators and multiline comments are also syntactically insignificant, but they guide the process for automatic semicolons insertion to make certain invalid token sequences become valid.
sec-array-initializer.title: Lexical grammar

The initial step of parsing is called lexical analysis, in which the text gets scanned from left to right and is converted into a sequence of individual, atomic input elements. Some input elements are insignificant to the interpreter, and will be stripped after this step  they include white space and comments. The others, including identifiers, keywords, literals, and punctuators (mostly operators), will be used for further syntax analysis. Line terminators and multiline comments are also syntactically insignificant, but they guide the process for automatic semicolons insertion to make certain invalid token sequences become valid.
prod-HexIntegerLiteral.title: Lexical grammar

sec-template-literals.name: template_literals
sec-template-literals.summary: Template literals are literals delimited with backtick (`) characters, allowing for multi-line strings, string interpolation with embedded expressions, and special constructs called tagged templates.
sec-template-literals.title: Template literals (Template strings)

prod-Elision.name: trailing_commas
prod-Elision.summary: Trailing commas (sometimes called "final commas") can be useful when adding new elements, parameters, or properties to JavaScript code. If you want to add a new property, you can add a new line without modifying the previously last line if that line already uses a trailing comma. This makes version-control diffs cleaner and editing code might be less troublesome.
prod-Elision.title: Trailing commas

sec-addition-operator-plus.name: addition
sec-addition-operator-plus.summary: The addition (+) operator produces the sum of numeric operands or string concatenation.
sec-addition-operator-plus.title: Addition (+)

sec-assignment-operators.name: addition_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The addition assignment (+=) operator performs addition (which is either numeric addition or string concatenation) on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Addition assignment (+=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The assignment (=) operator is used to assign a value to a variable. The assignment operation evaluates to the assigned value. Chaining the assignment operator is possible in order to assign a single value to multiple variables.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Assignment (=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_and_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise AND assignment (&=) operator performs bitwise AND on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise AND assignment (&=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_or_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise OR assignment (|=) operator performs bitwise OR on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise OR assignment (|=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: bitwise_xor_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The bitwise XOR assignment (^=) operator performs bitwise XOR on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Bitwise XOR assignment (^=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: division_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The division assignment (/=) operator performs division on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Division assignment (/=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: exponentiation_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The exponentiation assignment (**=) operator performs exponentiation on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Exponentiation assignment (**=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: left_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The left shift assignment (<<=) operator performs left shift on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Left shift assignment (<<=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: logical_and_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The logical AND assignment (x &&= y) operator only assigns if x is truthy.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Logical AND assignment (&&=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: logical_or_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The logical OR assignment (x ||= y) operator only assigns if x is falsy.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Logical OR assignment (||=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: multiplication_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The multiplication assignment (*=) operator performs multiplication on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Multiplication assignment (*=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: nullish_coalescing_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The nullish coalescing assignment (??=) operator, also known as the logical nullish assignment operator, only assigns if x is nullish (null or undefined).
sec-assignment-operators.title: Nullish coalescing assignment (??=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: remainder_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The remainder assignment (%=) operator performs remainder on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Remainder assignment (%=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The right shift assignment (>>=) operator performs right shift on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Right shift assignment (>>=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: subtraction_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The subtraction assignment (-=) operator performs subtraction on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Subtraction assignment (-=)

sec-assignment-operators.name: unsigned_right_shift_assignment
sec-assignment-operators.summary: The unsigned right shift assignment (>>>=) operator performs unsigned right shift on the two operands and assigns the result to the left operand.
sec-assignment-operators.title: Unsigned right shift assignment (>>>=)

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The async function keywords can be used to define an async function inside an expression.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function expression

sec-async-function-definitions.name: top_level
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The await operator is used to wait for a Promise and get its fulfillment value. It can only be used inside an async function or at the top level of a module.

nodejs.notes: Not supported in CommonJS modules.
Not supported in CommonJS modules.

sec-async-function-definitions.title: await

sec-async-function-definitions.name: await
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The await operator is used to wait for a Promise and get its fulfillment value. It can only be used inside an async function or at the top level of a module.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: await

sec-async-function-definitions.name: async_function
sec-async-function-definitions.summary: The async function declaration creates a binding of a new async function to a given name. The await keyword is permitted within the function body, enabling asynchronous, promise-based behavior to be written in a cleaner style and avoiding the need to explicitly configure promise chains.
sec-async-function-definitions.title: async function

sec-async-generator-function-definitions.name: async_generator_function
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.summary: The async function* keywords can be used to define an asynchronous generator function inside an expression.
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.title: async function* expression

sec-async-generator-function-definitions.name: async_generator_function
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.summary: The async function* declaration creates a binding of a new async generator function to a given name.
sec-async-generator-function-definitions.title: async function*

prod-BitwiseANDExpression.name: bitwise_and
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.summary: The bitwise AND (&) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation has a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of both operands are 1.
prod-BitwiseANDExpression.title: Bitwise AND (&)

sec-bitwise-not-operator.name: bitwise_not
sec-bitwise-not-operator.summary: The bitwise NOT (~) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation has a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bit of the operand is 0, and a 0 otherwise.
sec-bitwise-not-operator.title: Bitwise NOT (~)

prod-BitwiseORExpression.name: bitwise_or
prod-BitwiseORExpression.summary: The bitwise OR (|) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation has a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either or both operands are 1.
prod-BitwiseORExpression.title: Bitwise OR (|)

prod-BitwiseXORExpression.name: bitwise_xor
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.summary: The bitwise XOR (^) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation has a 1 in each bit position for which the corresponding bits of either but not both operands are 1.
prod-BitwiseXORExpression.title: Bitwise XOR (^)

sec-comma-operator.name: comma
sec-comma-operator.summary: The comma (,) operator evaluates each of its operands (from left to right) and returns the value of the last operand. This is commonly used to provide multiple updaters to a for loop's afterthought.
sec-comma-operator.title: Comma operator (,)

sec-conditional-operator.name: conditional
sec-conditional-operator.summary: The conditional (ternary) operator is the only JavaScript operator that takes three operands: a condition followed by a question mark (?), then an expression to execute if the condition is truthy followed by a colon (:), and finally the expression to execute if the condition is falsy. This operator is frequently used as an alternative to an if...else statement.
sec-conditional-operator.title: Conditional (ternary) operator

sec-postfix-decrement-operator.name: decrement
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.summary: The decrement (--) operator decrements (subtracts one from) its operand and returns the value before or after the decrement, depending on where the operator is placed.
sec-postfix-decrement-operator.title: Decrement (--)

sec-delete-operator.name: delete
sec-delete-operator.summary: The delete operator removes a property from an object. If the property's value is an object and there are no more references to the object, the object held by that property is eventually released automatically.
sec-delete-operator.title: delete operator

sec-destructuring-assignment.name: destructuring
sec-destructuring-assignment.summary: The destructuring assignment syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to unpack values from arrays, or properties from objects, into distinct variables.

firefox.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

sec-destructuring-assignment.title: Destructuring assignment

sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.name: destructuring
sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.summary: The destructuring assignment syntax is a JavaScript expression that makes it possible to unpack values from arrays, or properties from objects, into distinct variables.

firefox.notes: Firefox provided a non-standard destructuring implementation from Firefox 2 to 40.

sec-destructuring-binding-patterns.title: Destructuring assignment

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: division
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The division (/) operator produces the quotient of its operands where the left operand is the dividend and the right operand is the divisor.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Division (/)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: multiplication
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The multiplication (*) operator produces the product of the operands.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Multiplication (*)

sec-multiplicative-operators.name: remainder
sec-multiplicative-operators.summary: The remainder (%) operator returns the remainder left over when one operand is divided by a second operand. It always takes the sign of the dividend.
sec-multiplicative-operators.title: Remainder (%)

sec-equality-operators.name: equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The equality (==) operator checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict equality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Equality (==)

sec-equality-operators.name: inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The inequality (!=) operator checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the strict inequality operator, it attempts to convert and compare operands that are of different types.
sec-equality-operators.title: Inequality (!=)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_equality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict equality (===) operator checks whether its two operands are equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the equality operator, the strict equality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict equality (===)

sec-equality-operators.name: strict_inequality
sec-equality-operators.summary: The strict inequality (!==) operator checks whether its two operands are not equal, returning a Boolean result. Unlike the inequality operator, the strict inequality operator always considers operands of different types to be different.
sec-equality-operators.title: Strict inequality (!==)

sec-exp-operator.name: exponentiation
sec-exp-operator.summary: The exponentiation (**) operator returns the result of raising the first operand to the power of the second operand. It is equivalent to Math.pow(), except it also accepts BigInts as operands.
sec-exp-operator.title: Exponentiation (**)

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: generator_function
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* keyword can be used to define a generator function inside an expression.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function* expression

sec-generator-function-definitions.name: generator_function
sec-generator-function-definitions.summary: The function* declaration creates a binding of a new generator function to a given name. A generator function can be exited and later re-entered, with its context (variable bindings) saved across re-entrances.
sec-generator-function-definitions.title: function*

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than (>) operator returns true if the left operand is greater than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than (>)

sec-relational-operators.name: greater_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The greater than or equal (>=) operator returns true if the left operand is greater than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Greater than or equal (>=)

sec-relational-operators.name: in
sec-relational-operators.summary: The in operator returns true if the specified property is in the specified object or its prototype chain.
sec-relational-operators.title: in operator

sec-relational-operators.name: instanceof
sec-relational-operators.summary: The instanceof operator tests to see if the prototype property of a constructor appears anywhere in the prototype chain of an object. The return value is a boolean value. Its behavior can be customized with Symbol.hasInstance.
sec-relational-operators.title: instanceof

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than (<) operator returns true if the left operand is less than the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than (<)

sec-relational-operators.name: less_than_or_equal
sec-relational-operators.summary: The less than or equal (<=) operator returns true if the left operand is less than or equal to the right operand, and false otherwise.
sec-relational-operators.title: Less than or equal (<=)

sec-grouping-operator.name: grouping
sec-grouping-operator.summary: The grouping ( ) operator controls the precedence of evaluation in expressions. It also acts as a container for arbitrary expressions in certain syntactic constructs, where ambiguity or syntax errors would otherwise occur.
sec-grouping-operator.title: Grouping operator ( )

sec-import-calls.name: import
sec-import-calls.summary: The import() syntax, commonly called dynamic import, is a function-like expression that allows loading an ECMAScript module asynchronously and dynamically into a potentially non-module environment.

deno.notes: Bundled Deno applications (using `deno compile`) do not support dynamic imports

nodejs.notes: Dynamic import can be used in either CommonJS or ES module files, to import either CommonJS or ES module files. See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.
Dynamic import can be used in either CommonJS or ES module files, to import either CommonJS or ES module files. See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.

sec-import-calls.title: import()

prod-ImportMeta.name: import_meta
prod-ImportMeta.summary: The import.meta meta-property exposes context-specific metadata to a JavaScript module. It contains information about the module, such as the module's URL.
prod-ImportMeta.title: import.meta

sec-postfix-increment-operator.name: increment
sec-postfix-increment-operator.summary: The increment (++) operator increments (adds one to) its operand and returns the value before or after the increment, depending on where the operator is placed.
sec-postfix-increment-operator.title: Increment (++)

sec-left-shift-operator.name: left_shift
sec-left-shift-operator.summary: The left shift (<<) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation is the first operand shifted by the specified number of bits to the left. Excess bits shifted off to the left are discarded, and zero bits are shifted in from the right.
sec-left-shift-operator.title: Left shift (<<)

prod-LogicalANDExpression.name: logical_and
prod-LogicalANDExpression.summary: The logical AND (&&) (logical conjunction) operator for a set of boolean operands will be true if and only if all the operands are true. Otherwise it will be false.
prod-LogicalANDExpression.title: Logical AND (&&)

sec-logical-not-operator.name: logical_not
sec-logical-not-operator.summary: The logical NOT (!) (logical complement, negation) operator takes truth to falsity and vice versa. It is typically used with boolean (logical) values. When used with non-Boolean values, it returns false if its single operand can be converted to true; otherwise, returns true.
sec-logical-not-operator.title: Logical NOT (!)

prod-LogicalORExpression.name: logical_or
prod-LogicalORExpression.summary: The logical OR (||) (logical disjunction) operator for a set of operands is true if and only if one or more of its operands is true. It is typically used with boolean (logical) values. When it is, it returns a Boolean value. However, the || operator actually returns the value of one of the specified operands, so if this operator is used with non-Boolean values, it will return a non-Boolean value.
prod-LogicalORExpression.title: Logical OR (||)

sec-new-operator.name: new
sec-new-operator.summary: The new operator lets developers create an instance of a user-defined object type or of one of the built-in object types that has a constructor function.
sec-new-operator.title: new operator

sec-built-in-function-objects.name: new_target
sec-built-in-function-objects.summary: The new.target meta-property lets you detect whether a function or constructor was called using the new operator. In constructors and functions invoked using the new operator, new.target returns a reference to the constructor or function that new was called upon. In normal function calls, new.target is undefined.
sec-built-in-function-objects.title: new.target

sec-null-value.name: null
sec-null-value.summary: The null value represents the intentional absence of any object value. It is one of JavaScript's primitive values and is treated as falsy for boolean operations.
sec-null-value.title: null

prod-CoalesceExpression.name: nullish_coalescing
prod-CoalesceExpression.summary: The nullish coalescing (??) operator is a logical operator that returns its right-hand side operand when its left-hand side operand is null or undefined, and otherwise returns its left-hand side operand.
prod-CoalesceExpression.title: Nullish coalescing operator (??)

sec-object-initializer.name: object_initializer
sec-object-initializer.summary: An object initializer is a comma-delimited list of zero or more pairs of property names and associated values of an object, enclosed in curly braces ({}). Objects can also be initialized using Object.create() or by invoking a constructor function with the new operator.
sec-object-initializer.title: Object initializer

prod-OptionalExpression.name: optional_chaining
prod-OptionalExpression.summary: The optional chaining (?.) operator accesses an object's property or calls a function. If the object accessed or function called using this operator is undefined or null, the expression short circuits and evaluates to undefined instead of throwing an error.
prod-OptionalExpression.title: Optional chaining (?.)

sec-property-accessors.name: property_accessors
sec-property-accessors.summary: Property accessors provide access to an object's properties by using the dot notation or the bracket notation.
sec-property-accessors.title: Property accessors

sec-signed-right-shift-operator.name: right_shift
sec-signed-right-shift-operator.summary: The right shift (>>) operator returns a number or BigInt whose binary representation is the first operand shifted by the specified number of bits to the right. Excess bits shifted off to the right are discarded, and copies of the leftmost bit are shifted in from the left. This operation is also called "sign-propagating right shift" or "arithmetic right shift", because the sign of the resulting number is the same as the sign of the first operand.
sec-signed-right-shift-operator.title: Right shift (>>)

prod-SpreadElement.name: spread_in_arrays
prod-SpreadElement.summary: The spread (...) syntax allows an iterable, such as an array or string, to be expanded in places where zero or more arguments (for function calls) or elements (for array literals) are expected. In an object literal, the spread syntax enumerates the properties of an object and adds the key-value pairs to the object being created.
prod-SpreadElement.title: Spread syntax (...)
