sec-subtraction-operator-minus.name: subtraction
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.summary: The subtraction (-) operator subtracts the two operands, producing their difference.
sec-subtraction-operator-minus.title: Subtraction (-)

sec-super-keyword.name: super
sec-super-keyword.summary: The super keyword is used to access properties on an object literal or class's [[Prototype]], or invoke a superclass's constructor.
sec-super-keyword.title: super

sec-this-keyword.name: this
sec-this-keyword.summary: A function's this keyword behaves a little differently in JavaScript compared to other languages. It also has some differences between strict mode and non-strict mode.
sec-this-keyword.title: this

sec-typeof-operator.name: typeof
sec-typeof-operator.summary: The typeof operator returns a string indicating the type of the operand's value.
sec-typeof-operator.title: typeof

sec-unary-minus-operator.name: unary_negation
sec-unary-minus-operator.summary: The unary negation (-) operator precedes its operand and negates it.
sec-unary-minus-operator.title: Unary negation (-)

sec-unary-plus-operator.name: unary_plus
sec-unary-plus-operator.summary: The unary plus (+) operator precedes its operand and evaluates to its operand but attempts to convert it into a number, if it isn't already.
sec-unary-plus-operator.title: Unary plus (+)

sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.name: unsigned_right_shift
sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.summary: The unsigned right shift (>>>) operator returns a number whose binary representation is the first operand shifted by the specified number of bits to the right. Excess bits shifted off to the right are discarded, and zero bits are shifted in from the left. This operation is also called "zero-filling right shift", because the sign bit becomes 0, so the resulting number is always positive. Unsigned right shift does not accept BigInt values.
sec-unsigned-right-shift-operator.title: Unsigned right shift (>>>)

sec-void-operator.name: void
sec-void-operator.summary: The void operator evaluates the given expression and then returns undefined.
sec-void-operator.title: void operator

prod-YieldExpression.name: yield
prod-YieldExpression.summary: The yield operator is used to pause and resume a generator function.

notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.
Starting with Firefox 29, an IteratorResult object returned for completed generator function.

prod-YieldExpression.title: yield

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.name: yield_star
sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.summary: The yield* operator is used to delegate to another iterable object, such as a Generator.

firefox.notes: Starting with Firefox 33, the parsing of the yield expression has been updated to conform with the ES2015 specification.

sec-generator-function-definitions-runti.title: yield*

prod-DecimalEscape.name: backreference
prod-DecimalEscape.summary: A backreference refers to the submatch of a previous capturing group and matches the same text as that group. For named capturing groups, you may prefer to use the named backreference syntax.
prod-DecimalEscape.title: Backreference: \1, \2

prod-Atom.name: capturing_group
prod-Atom.summary: A capturing group groups a subpattern, allowing you to apply a quantifier to the entire group or use disjunctions within it. It memorizes information about the subpattern match, so that you can refer back to it later with a backreference, or access the information through the match results.
prod-Atom.title: Capturing group: (...)

prod-Atom.name: named_capturing_group
prod-Atom.summary: A named capturing group is a particular kind of capturing group that allows to give a name to the group. The group's matching result can later be identified by this name instead of by its index in the pattern.
prod-Atom.title: Named capturing group: (?<name>...)

prod-Atom.name: non_capturing_group
prod-Atom.summary: A non-capturing group groups a subpattern, allowing you to apply a quantifier to the entire group or use disjunctions within it. It acts like the grouping operator in JavaScript expressions, and unlike capturing groups, it does not memorize the matched text, allowing for better performance and avoiding confusion when the pattern also contains useful capturing groups.
prod-Atom.title: Non-capturing group: (?:...)

prod-Atom.name: wildcard
prod-Atom.summary: A wildcard matches all characters except line terminators. It also matches line terminators if the s flag is set.
prod-Atom.title: Wildcard: .

prod-CharacterClass.name: character_class
prod-CharacterClass.summary: A character class matches any character in or not in a custom set of characters. When the v flag is enabled, it can also be used to match finite-length strings.
prod-CharacterClass.title: Character class: [...], [^...]

prod-CharacterClassEscape.name: character_class_escape
prod-CharacterClassEscape.summary: A character class escape is an escape sequence that represents a set of characters.
prod-CharacterClassEscape.title: Character class escape: \d, \D, \w, \W, \s, \S

prod-CharacterClassEscape.name: unicode_character_class_escape
prod-CharacterClassEscape.summary: A unicode character class escape is a kind of character class escape that matches a set of characters specified by a Unicode property. It's only supported in Unicode-aware mode. When the v flag is enabled, it can also be used to match finite-length strings.
prod-CharacterClassEscape.title: Unicode character class escape: \p{...}, \P{...}

prod-CharacterEscape.name: character_escape
prod-CharacterEscape.summary: A character escape represents a character that may not be able to be conveniently represented in its literal form.
prod-CharacterEscape.title: Character escape: \n, \u{...}

prod-Disjunction.name: disjunction
prod-Disjunction.summary: A disjunction specifies multiple alternatives. Any alternative matching the input causes the entire disjunction to be matched.
prod-Disjunction.title: Disjunction: |

prod-Assertion.name: input_boundary_assertion
prod-Assertion.summary: An input boundary assertion checks if the current position in the string is an input boundary. An input boundary is the start or end of the string; or, if the m flag is set, the start or end of a line.
prod-Assertion.title: Input boundary assertion: ^, $

prod-Assertion.name: lookahead_assertion
prod-Assertion.summary: A lookahead assertion "looks ahead": it attempts to match the subsequent input with the given pattern, but it does not consume any of the input  if the match is successful, the current position in the input stays the same.
prod-Assertion.title: Lookahead assertion: (?=...), (?!...)

prod-Assertion.name: lookbehind_assertion
prod-Assertion.summary: A lookbehind assertion "looks behind": it attempts to match the previous input with the given pattern, but it does not consume any of the input  if the match is successful, the current position in the input stays the same. It matches each atom in its pattern in the reverse order.
prod-Assertion.title: Lookbehind assertion: (?<=...), (?<!...)

prod-Assertion.name: word_boundary_assertion
prod-Assertion.summary: A word boundary assertion checks if the current position in the string is a word boundary. A word boundary is where the next character is a word character and the previous character is not a word character, or vice versa.
prod-Assertion.title: Word boundary assertion: \b, \B

prod-PatternCharacter.name: literal_character
prod-PatternCharacter.summary: A literal character specifies exactly itself to be matched in the input text.
prod-PatternCharacter.title: Literal character: a, b

prod-AtomEscape.name: named_backreference
prod-AtomEscape.summary: A named backreference refers to the submatch of a previous named capturing group and matches the same text as that group. For unnamed capturing groups, you need to use the normal backreference syntax.
prod-AtomEscape.title: Named backreference: \k<name>

prod-Quantifier.name: quantifier
prod-Quantifier.summary: A quantifier repeats an atom a certain number of times. The quantifier is placed after the atom it applies to.
prod-Quantifier.title: Quantifier: *, +, ?, {n}, {n,}, {n,m}

sec-block.name: block
sec-block.summary: A block statement is used to group zero or more statements. The block is delimited by a pair of braces ("curly brackets") and contains a list of zero or more statements and declarations.
sec-block.title: block

sec-break-statement.name: break
sec-break-statement.summary: The break statement terminates the current loop or switch statement and transfers program control to the statement following the terminated statement. It can also be used to jump past a labeled statement when used within that labeled statement.
sec-break-statement.title: break

sec-let-and-const-declarations.name: const
sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: The const declaration declares block-scoped local variables. The value of a constant can't be changed through reassignment using the assignment operator, but if a constant is an object, its properties can be added, updated, or removed.

notes: Before Firefox 13, const is implemented, but re-assignment is not failing.
Before Firefox 46, a TypeError was thrown on redeclaration instead of a SyntaxError.

sec-let-and-const-declarations.title: const

sec-let-and-const-declarations.name: let
sec-let-and-const-declarations.summary: The let declaration declares re-assignable, block-scoped local variables, optionally initializing each to a value.

notes: Before Firefox 44, let is only available to code blocks in HTML wrapped in a <script type="application/javascript;version=1.7"> block (or higher version) and has different semantics (e.g. no temporal dead zone).
Before Firefox 46, a TypeError is thrown on redeclaration instead of a SyntaxError.
Firefox 54 adds support of let in workers.

ie.notes: In Internet Explorer, let within a for loop initializer does not create a separate variable for each loop iteration as defined by ES2015. Instead, it behaves as though the loop were wrapped in a scoping block with the let immediately before the loop.

sec-let-and-const-declarations.title: let

sec-continue-statement.name: continue
sec-continue-statement.summary: The continue statement terminates execution of the statements in the current iteration of the current or labeled loop, and continues execution of the loop with the next iteration.
sec-continue-statement.title: continue

sec-debugger-statement.name: debugger
sec-debugger-statement.summary: The debugger statement invokes any available debugging functionality, such as setting a breakpoint. If no debugging functionality is available, this statement has no effect.
sec-debugger-statement.title: debugger

sec-do-while-statement.name: do_while
sec-do-while-statement.summary: The do...while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement until the test condition evaluates to false. The condition is evaluated after executing the statement, resulting in the specified statement executing at least once.
sec-do-while-statement.title: do...while

sec-empty-statement.name: empty
sec-empty-statement.summary: An empty statement is used to provide no statement, although the JavaScript syntax would expect one.
sec-empty-statement.title: empty

sec-exports.name: default
sec-exports.summary: The export declaration is used to export values from a JavaScript module. Exported values can then be imported into other programs with the import declaration or dynamic import. The value of an imported binding is subject to change in the module that exports it  when a module updates the value of a binding that it exports, the update will be visible in its imported value.

sec-for-statement.name: for
sec-for-statement.summary: The for statement creates a loop that consists of three optional expressions, enclosed in parentheses and separated by semicolons, followed by a statement (usually a block statement) to be executed in the loop.
sec-for-statement.title: for

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_await_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for await...of statement creates a loop iterating over async iterable objects as well as sync iterables. This statement can only be used in contexts where await can be used, which includes inside an async function body and in a module.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for await...of

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_in
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...in statement iterates over all enumerable string properties of an object (ignoring properties keyed by symbols), including inherited enumerable properties.
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...in

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.name: for_of
sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.summary: The for...of statement executes a loop that operates on a sequence of values sourced from an iterable object. Iterable objects include instances of built-ins such as Array, String, TypedArray, Map, Set, NodeList (and other DOM collections), as well as the arguments object, generators produced by generator functions, and user-defined iterables.

firefox.notes: Before Firefox 51, using the for...of loop construct with the const keyword threw a SyntaxError ("missing = in const declaration").

sec-for-in-and-for-of-statements.title: for...of

sec-if-statement.name: if_else
sec-if-statement.summary: The if...else statement executes a statement if a specified condition is truthy. If the condition is falsy, another statement in the optional else clause will be executed.
sec-if-statement.title: if...else

sec-imports.name: import
sec-imports.summary: The static import declaration is used to import read-only live bindings which are exported by another module. The imported bindings are called live bindings because they are updated by the module that exported the binding, but cannot be re-assigned by the importing module.

nodejs.notes: Modules must either have a filename ending in .mjs, or the nearest parent package.json file must contain "type": "module". See Node's ECMAScript Modules documentation for more details.

sec-imports.title: import

sec-labelled-statements.name: label
sec-labelled-statements.summary: A labeled statement is any statement that is prefixed with an identifier. You can jump to this label using a break or continue statement nested within the labeled statement.
sec-labelled-statements.title: label

sec-return-statement.name: return
sec-return-statement.summary: The return statement ends function execution and specifies a value to be returned to the function caller.
sec-return-statement.title: return

sec-switch-statement.name: switch
sec-switch-statement.summary: The switch statement evaluates an expression, matching the expression's value against a series of case clauses, and executes statements after the first case clause with a matching value, until a break statement is encountered. The default clause of a switch statement will be jumped to if no case matches the expression's value.
sec-switch-statement.title: switch

sec-throw-statement.name: throw
sec-throw-statement.summary: The throw statement throws a user-defined exception. Execution of the current function will stop (the statements after throw won't be executed), and control will be passed to the first catch block in the call stack. If no catch block exists among caller functions, the program will terminate.
sec-throw-statement.title: throw

sec-try-statement.name: try_catch
sec-try-statement.summary: The try...catch statement is comprised of a try block and either a catch block, a finally block, or both. The code in the try block is executed first, and if it throws an exception, the code in the catch block will be executed. The code in the finally block will always be executed before control flow exits the entire construct.
sec-try-statement.title: try...catch

sec-variable-statement.name: var
sec-variable-statement.summary: The var statement declares function-scoped or globally-scoped variables, optionally initializing each to a value.
sec-variable-statement.title: var

sec-while-statement.name: while
sec-while-statement.summary: The while statement creates a loop that executes a specified statement as long as the test condition evaluates to true. The condition is evaluated before executing the statement.
sec-while-statement.title: while
